Part 1: Introduction¶

Since 1996, Pokemon has been touching the hearts of millions, selling over 240 million copies of the main franchise alone. Cute mascots combined with simple, rewarding gameplay loops provide an enjoyable experience for every type of player. Surprisingly, these cute pokemon hide a deep, mathematical world underneath them. The mechanics of pokemon have always been complex, but abstracted enough such that they don’t hold too much of a bearing for casual players. However, for the hardcore, optimization of Pokemon gameplay is a rich experience.

With this project, my goal is to determine what makes a Pokemon competitively viable. I will scrape information about Pokemon and process it to figure out how to judge the strength of a Pokemon! Along the way, I will answer some popular questions about the competitive Pokemon scene, such as the importance of certain moves, the strength of newer vs. older pokemon, and the impact of the base properties of Pokemon!

What is Competitive Pokemon?¶

If you know a decent amount about Pokemon, you can skip this section and hop right into the data collection!¶

In competitive Pokemon, players build a team of 6 pokemon and have them battle each other. In single battles, Pokemon come out one at a time, and in double battles, they come out two at a time. Pokemon use moves to damage the enemy pokemon until their health goes to zero, at which point they faint. When all your Pokemon faint, you lose.

So, as a competitive player, how do you choose the best 6 pokemon to build your ideal team? First, let's talk about what a pokemon is in terms of data that is important to a competitive player. Every Pokemon has 6 stats, types, moves, and abilities. These are what discern Pokemon from eachother in a competitive sense.

A bit of background information about Pokemon¶

The 6 stats are as follows:

  • Health Points (HP): Health Points indicate the amount of damage a pokemon can take before dying.
  • Attack (Atk): Attack is related to damage for physical type moves. More attack is more damage dealt.
  • Defense (Def): Defense is related to damage recieved for physical type moves. More defense is less damage taken.
  • Special Attack (SpA): Special Attack is like attack, but for special type moves.
  • Special Defense (SpD): Special Defense is like defense, but for special type moves.
  • Speed (Spe): Speed determines the move order of pokemon. Pokemon with a higher speed stat go first.

Types are properties of Pokemon and their moves.

The Pokemon Typing of a Pokemon determine the damage they take from certain moves and effects, and also play a part in the damage calculation of certain moves. For instance, if a Pokemon is a fire-type, they will recieve more damage from water-type moves, and less damage from grass-type moves. Additionally, if that Pokemon were to use a fire-type move, they would deal more damage. Pokemon can have one or two types.

All Pokemon have a set of moves that they can learn. Moves have Move Typing, and can either be physical, special, or status-inducing. "Coverage" is the ability for an individual Pokemon or a team of Pokemon to give and take damage across a variety of types is called, and is a great indicator of how flexible a pokemon can be on the battlefield. A Pokemon can only bring 4 moves into battle at a time, meaning that we have to choose from our pool carefully.

Abilities are unique points about Pokemon that can effect the tides of battle!

All Pokemon have a set of abilities which have a unique effect. These can range from immunity to certain moves, creating certain weather or terrain conditions, or boosting the effects of certain moves. Pokemon have anywhere from 1 to 3 abilities to choose from, and can only have one in effect at a time.

Part 2: Data Collection, Scraping from APIs and HTML¶

The first part of the data pipeline is collection. We're going to start out with importing stuff that we use to collect the data. The documentation for the libraries we use is linked in the descriptions!

  • BeautifulSoup is a Python library used to scrape from webpages. It has great HTML and LXML parsers to help you get all the raw text that you need.
  • re is Python's regular expression library. Regular expressions are powerful tools used to quickly match substrings.
  • requests is an HTTP library that makes it easier to send requests to sites.
  • json, JavaScript Object Notation, is a syntax used to communicate data. A lot of the data stored online and from APIs comes to us in this form, and this plugin allows us to parse it much easier.
  • numpy is a package for scientific computation on arrays. This is fundamental to our next package...
  • pandas is a powerful data analysis toolkit for python. Perhaps the most important package, this introduces the DataFrame object, a fantastic tool for data storage and ease of analysis.
  • time and clear_output are going to be used to make sure we don't overload websites with requests. More on this later.

One thing to note is that the scraping can take a lot of time, so i've included a flag that lets you use the data that i've scraped by importing it from a file. With all that out of the way, let's import!

Requesting Data From an API¶

The API we're scraping from for this project is PokeAPI. Now, before starting any code for scraping from an API, we should note a few things. Firstly, we should take a look at the documentation for the API. This lets us know what we should request from the API, and the information it can provide, along with the format. We see that all we do is send requests with the requests plugin, and recieve our information back in JSON format.

One thing to note is that because the API is free-use and does not require any authentication, we have to be careful with how many requests we send. PokeAPI asks us to limit ourselves to 100 REQUESTS PER MINUTE, and we should respect that, which explains why I imported the time library.

However, waiting for all the stuff to download is a tall task to ask. So, I've exported the data as a CSV that you can [download here]. IF you want to try downloading it all yourself, just remember to change the flag in that first block of code. Let's start with a simple example.

In [2]:
pokes_by_gen = []
for i in range(1, 8):
    url = 'https://pokeapi.co/api/v2/generation/' + str(i)
    response = requests.get(url)
    cur_gen = response.json() if response and response.status_code == 200 else None
    poke_list = []
    for j in range (0, len(cur_gen['pokemon_species'])):
        poke_list.append(cur_gen['pokemon_species'][j]['name'])
    pokes_by_gen.append(poke_list)    
    
def find_gen(name):
    for i in range(0, len(pokes_by_gen)):
        if name in pokes_by_gen[i]:
            return i+1
    return np.nan

This block of code forms the request URL of the current pokemon. A response code of 200 indicates that we successfully recieved the data back from the API. the .json() method converts the response to a JSON load, which allows us to index the elements with ease!

url = 'https://pokeapi.co/api/v2/generation/' + str(i)
response = requests.get(url)
cur_gen = response.json() if response and response.status_code == 200 else None

We basically iterate through all 7 of the generations, then iterate through the list of pokemon that were introduced in that generation! find_gen() is a function we write to help us find the generation of a pokemon based on its name!

Now, let's get into the meat of the scraping.

# Check the flag to see if we will scrape it raw!
if NEW_CSV_FLAG:
    pokemon_cols = ['dex_id', 'name', 'spe', 'spd', 'spa', 'dfn', 'atk', 'hp', 
                    'type_1', 'type_2', 'move_list', 'gen']
    df_pokemon = pd.DataFrame(columns = pokemon_cols)
    
    # This is the amount of pokemon that are in generation 7!
    for i in range(1, 808):
        
        # Make sure we don't overload the pokeAPI with requests!
        time.sleep(0.6)
        
        url = 'https://pokeapi.co/api/v2/pokemon/' + str(i)
        response = requests.get(url)
        cur_data = response.json() if response and response.status_code == 200 else None
        # Something went wrong?
        if cur_data == None:
            continue
        
        # ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        # This section is about getting the information that we want! See below for more info.
        dex_id = cur_data['id']
        name = cur_data['name']
        gen = find_gen(name)
        spe = cur_data['stats'][0]['base_stat']
        spd = cur_data['stats'][1]['base_stat']
        spa = cur_data['stats'][2]['base_stat']
        dfn = cur_data['stats'][3]['base_stat']
        atk = cur_data['stats'][4]['base_stat']
        hp  = cur_data['stats'][5]['base_stat']
        
        # Check if current pokemon is monotype or dual-typed
        type_1 = cur_data['types'][0]['type']['name']
        if (len(cur_data['types']) == 2):
            type_2 = cur_data['types'][1]['type']['name']
        else:
            type_2 = np.nan

        # Get the moves that the pokemon can potentially learn!
        move_list = []
        for j in range(0, len(cur_data['moves'])):
            move_list.append(cur_data['moves'][j]['move']['name'])
        # ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        
        new_pokemon = pd.Series([dex_id, name, spe, spd, spa, dfn, atk, hp, type_1, type_2, move_list, gen], index = pokemon_cols)
        df_pokemon = df_pokemon.append(new_pokemon, ignore_index = True)
    
        # Debug output if making your own CSV
        if DEBUG_FLAG:
            clear_output()
            print('Processing Pokedex Entry Number: ' + str(dex_id) + '; Name: ' + name)
            
    df_pokemon.to_csv('pokemon_list.csv')
else:
    
    # Don't request from the API, read my CSV
    df_pokemon = pd.read_csv('pokemon_list.csv')
    # This line cleans up the formatting of the read_csv() method to match our OG dataframe.
    df_pokemon = df_pokemon.loc[:, ~df_pokemon.columns.str.contains('^Unnamed')]

Scraping Data From an HTML Page¶

We're going to be scraping from three different sites.

  • PokemonDB is a community site that aims to make information about Pokemon clear and available.
  • Bulbapedia is a community wiki with a ton of information about everything Pokemon!44
  • Smogon's StrategyDex is a site holding the competitive information of pokemon in a generation. Since we're working with generation 7, we'll use the Sun/Moon pages.

Lets start with the easier of the three to work with.

We're going to get the information about all the moves, all the abilities, and all the items in Pokemon. These are respectively stored on seperate pages on PokemonDB. The information is stored in tables directly coded into the HTML format, which makes it significantly easier to parse. Let's make a dataframe for each of these pages!

Moves¶

In [4]:
if NEW_CSV_FLAG:
    response = requests.get('http://pokemondb.net/move/all')
    soup = bs(response.text, 'html.parser')
    tab = soup.find("table")
    tab_rows = tab.find_all('tr')
    move_cols = ['name', 'type', 'category', 'power', 'acc', 'pp', 'tm', 'effect', 'chance']
    df_moves = pd.DataFrame(columns = move_cols)
    for i in range(1, len(tab_rows)):
        tab_entries = tab_rows[i].find_all('td')
        
        # We do this to match the format of the moves 
        row = [t.text for t in tab_entries]
        # Get the value we need, telling us category of move
        row[2] = tab_entries[2]['data-sort-value']
        new_move = pd.Series(row, index = move_cols)
        df_moves = df_moves.append(new_move, ignore_index = True)
    df_moves.to_csv('moves_list.csv')
else:
    
    # Don't scrape from HTML
    df_moves = pd.read_csv('moves_list.csv')
    df_moves = df_moves.loc[:, ~df_moves.columns.str.contains('^Unnamed')]

Lets take a look at some of the new methods that were introduced to us here.

  • bs takes two parameters and initializes BeautifulSoup. The first parameter is the text of what we want to parse. The second parameter is the type of parser we will use, in this case, the HTML parser.
  • find() and find_all() are BeautifulSoup methods that find the HTML tags and return their contents.
  • tbody,tr, and td are all HTML tag types that involve the HTML table. They hold the stuff that we extract with the aforementioned methods.

Now let's work on the fussy one...

This site holds the competitive-relevant information of Pokemon. We want to know the following:

  • The format/tier that the Pokemon is categorized in
  • Whether or not it's a fully evolved Pokemon
  • The abilities it can have
  • The competitive ideals of the following for the Pokemon:
    • Moveset
    • Ability
    • Held Item
    • Nature

The site has a list of all the Pokemon in the generation, but it's not in the same format as the PokeAPI. This is where things get rough. Unlike PokeAPI, Smogon's Dex lists alternate forms of Pokemon as individual entries.

This is a fairly easy problem to deal with, as we can just clean up the alternative forms later and collect the data anyway. However, there's a much bigger issue at hand. Smogon's Dex only lists competitive-relevant information about Pokemon. This means that if a Pokemon isn't relevant to the scene, it just wont have any information on that Pokemon's page. Take a look.

Aegislash: Competitive-relevant Aipom: Non-Relevant

This means that if the Pokemon or any of its forms aren't competitively relevant, the competitive ideals will be completely missing! To account for this, we'll simply put all the competitive fields in as np.nan if the page is missing, indicating the missingness of the relevant information!

This code looks pretty different from our HTML scraping of PokemonDB. That's because there was a big issue with the parsing: All the information is loaded onto a script that runs on the pages.

To fix this, we just use the find() method to get the script contents, then clean it up with strip() and replace() to get something that can be converted into a JSON load with the loads() method. Now, like earlier with the PokeAPI's JSON, we have to figure out what indeces to access to get the right information.

Again, we can use a JSON viewer to see the way that the data is formatted. Here, I additionally used json's keys() method to find the names of the indeces that we want to access, and also the len() method for lists.

That's how we get the neater lines of code like this:

moves = load['injectRpcs'][2][1]['strategies'][0]['movesets'][0]['moveslots']

Everything else is the same as before. Now, let's get the type weaknesses, which were also in the script string from Smogon!

Data Tidying!¶

This is the part of the project where we clean up and process our data for later use. In the scraping and collection, we did do a little bit of tidying with the np.nan, but there's a lot more we can do. Here's what we should aim to have at the end of this section:

  • Uniform formatting for the same data
  • Remove irrelevant information
  • Unified DataFrames where applicable
  • Add any information that would be relevant later as new columns in the DataFrame

Let's take account of all the dataframes we have now and the data they respectively hold.

  • df_pokemon came from PokeAPI, and holds pokemon names, their stats, their type(s), a list of moves they can learn, and the generation that they were introduced in.
  • df_moves came from PokemonDB, and holds move names, their type, their category, their power, their accuracy, their PP, their TM, their secondary effect, and the probability of triggering it.
  • df_abils came from PokemonDB, and holds ability names, the amount of pokemon that use them, their effects, and the generation they were introduced.
  • df_items came from PokemonDB, and holds item names, their category, and their description.
  • df_natures holds a list of the natures, their japanese names, and the stats they affect.
  • df_smogon came from Smogon, and holds pokemon names, the format/tier they belong in, whether or not they are a final evolution, their potential abilities, and their competitive ideals for moveset, ability, hold item, and nature.
  • df_types came from Smogon, and holds a set of type weaknesses to moves.

Uniformed formatting¶

Let's start with the Smogon dataframe. Something to note is that due to the way that loads() parsed our strings, what appeared to be lists of strings actually is a string itself. How do we account for this? Well, a property to note is that if the item was originally a list, then it will have the brackets [] in the string. Additionally, it will have commas if there were multiple objects. We just have to write a function (process_entries) that:

  1. Checks if the item is a string, and if not, just return the same thing
  2. Checks if the item was originally a list, and if not, returns the string
  3. Removes any characters that are not commas or alphanumeric
  4. Returns a list with the original strings.

While we're there, we can set a format for all strings to use. Let's have them all be lowercase, and replace spaces with dashes! This will be process_strings.

This essentially flattens the lists for us, making it easier to parse. At the same time, we can remove all spaces and make all the strings lowercase as a way to uniformly format everything!

In addition, for Smogon's dataframe specifically, let's change all the missing formats to Limbo, as that is the classification for "unclassified" Pokemon.

In [10]:
def process_strings(s):
    return re.sub(' ','-', s.lower().strip())
    
def process_entries(item):
    if type(item) == str:
        if '[' in str(item):
            ret = re.sub('[\[\]\']', '', item)
            ret = ret.split(',')
            ret = [process_strings(x) for x in ret]
            return ret
        return process_strings(item)
    return item

for col in df_smogon.columns:
    df_smogon[col] = df_smogon[col].map(lambda l: process_entries(l))

df_smogon['smogon_format'] = df_smogon['smogon_format'].fillna('limbo')

Removing Irrelevant Information¶

Oh boy, this is my favorite part. Let's start culling. The methods we'll use the most here is drop(), a method for Pandas Dataframes. This allows us to drop specific columns, which helps us cull those useless ones. The .columns property of dataframes can also help us find which columns are useless.

The dataframes which hold the most useless information are the ones where we don't query specific information. This essentially means that all the table related dataframes are bloated. Lets take a look.

So, lets look at what we can drop from each dataframe.

  • For df_moves, we don't really need to know the pp, the tm, the effect, or the chance at all, so we can drop those.
  • For df_abils, we don't really care about the amount of pokemon that ability, we care more about the amount of competitive-relevant pokemon that would choose that ability over other options. We also don't care about the generation in which it was introduced.
  • For df_items, we actually don't care about certain items. Only hold items are relevant to competitive pokemon.
  • for df_natures, we really only care about the stats that the nature increases or decreases.

Unifying Dataframes¶

For another project, we may have to unify more dataframes where appropriate, but here, we can just unify df_pokemon and df_smogon as the information they hold is all about individual pokemon. Let's talk briefly about how we'll unify the frames.

Pandas' merge() method allows us to specify how we want to combine these dataframes.

  • By merging on name, we use the name column of both dataframes to see which entries correspond to one another.
  • By performing an inner merge, we make sure that ONLY rows that exist in both dataframes get kept.

Let's merge these two into a master datafram, called df_master.

In [23]:

def move_category_count(lst, cat):
    count = 0;
    try:
        for i in lst:
            temp = df_moves.loc[df_moves['name'] == i]
            # if move is not in list? Maybe an error.
            try:
                if temp.iloc[0]['category'] == cat:
                    count += 1
            except:
                ;
    except:
            ;
    return count
def bl_func(s):
    return "bl" in str(s)
def make_type(row):
    lst = []
    lst.append(str(row.type_1))
    if (str(row.type_2) != 'nan'):
        lst.append(str(row.type_2))
    return lst
def damaging_move_types(lst):
    typel = [];
    try: 
        for i in lst:
            temp = df_moves.loc[df_moves['name'] == i]
            try:
                if (temp.iloc[0]['category'] == 'special' or 
                    temp.iloc[0]['category'] == 'physical'):
                    typel.append(temp.iloc[0]['type'])
            except:
                ;
    except:
        ;
    return typel
def cover_ct(row):
    count = 0
    for t in pokemon_types:
        cover_string = "cover_" + t
        if (row[cover_string]):
            count += 1
    return count

smog_forms = ['limbo', 'lc', 'pu', 'nu', 'ru', 'uu', 'ou', 'uber']
def limboify_form(s):
    if s in smog_forms or bl_func(s):
        return s
    return 'limbo'
  • move_category_count() takes a list of moves, then counts the number of moves of a specific category. We'll use this to determine the types of moves a Pokemon has available to their arsenal.
  • bl_func() takes a string and checks to see if it contains bl, which we'll use to determine if a pokemon is borderline in its tier.
  • make_type() makes a list of the types a pokemon has. This will be useful to us later, but is an intermediate form of information.
  • damaging_move_types() returns a list of the types of the damaging moves. We'll use this later to determine coverage!
  • limboify_form() converts any Pokemon NOT in a standard format to limbo, the "rejects" of the bunch.

Alright. Now let's update the ability table. What do we possibly want to learn from a pokemon's abilities? Because of the qualitative nature of pokemon abilities, it's quite difficult to determine the "goodness" of an ability. We will, however, try.

While abilities are qualitative, the chance of choosing one as the best from a pool of abilities is not. We can use this as sort of an estimator of how good an ability is. If it's really good, then we're likely to pick it more often. However, we should note that this estimator can backfire when considering abilities that are unique to pokemon.

In [32]:
df_abils['total_ct'] = 0
for form in smog_forms: 
    df_abils[form] = 0
    s = form + '_ratio'
    df_abils[s] = 0.0

    # Update Ability Table
    for a in row['abilities']:
        df_abils.loc[df_abils.name == a, 'total_ct'] += 1
    try:
        for a in row['ideal_ability']:
            df_abils.loc[df_abils.name == a, form] += 1
            df_abils.loc[df_abils.name == a, s] += 1/len(row['abilities'])
    except:
        ;

Lets also add counts for the amount of types that we are weak to, resist, deal extra damage to, and deal less damage to. We write a function called weak_or_resist that returns the count of resistances/weaknesses to help us.

In [36]:
def weak_or_resist(lst, flag):
    count = 0;
    for e in lst:
        if flag and e < 1.0:
            count += 1
        if not flag and e > 1.0:
            count += 1
    return count

df_types['resist'] = 0.0
df_types['weak'] = 0.0
df_types['supereffective'] = 0.0
df_types['notveryeffective'] = 0.0
for idx, row in df_types.iterrows():
    s = row['attacking_type']
    df_types.at[idx, 'resist'] = weak_or_resist(df_types[s], True)
    df_types.at[idx, 'weak'] = weak_or_resist(df_types[s], False)
    supereffective = 0
    notveryeffective = 0
    for t in pokemon_types:
        if row[t] > 1:
            supereffective += 1
        if row[t] < 1:
            notveryeffective += 1
    df_types.at[idx, 'supereffective'] = supereffective
    df_types.at[idx, 'notveryeffective'] = notveryeffective

df_types['total_ct'] = 0
for form in smog_forms:

            df_types.loc[df_types.attacking_type == t, tier] += 1
        except:
            ;

Exploratory Data Analysis and Visualization¶

This part of the data pipeline is where we start identifying some of the important things about our data. We can start identifying trends, and we can also start to identify data points that seem to break the norm a bit. All of this means that we can begin to make some generalizations about Pokemon in a competitive sense.

So, let's start with some imports and talk about the libraries that we'll be using here.

In [37]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Some of the libraries that we're going to use have been used before, but there are some new ones to talk about too.

  • numpy contains a lot of methods that give us summary statistics for their arrays, such as the mean or median values of a numerical set.
  • pandas will allow us to sort lists and sets in a way that lets us view significant factors.
  • matplotlib.pyplot is a library that helps us create and display various plots, which will help us visualize some of the trends that may be more difficult to notice in raw, numerical data.
  • seaborn is a higher level abstraction of visualization and plotting on matplotlib. It's essentially a wrapper that passes a cleaner set of parameters to matplotlib to display a plot.

With that being said, let's get started on some visualization. Based on our dataframes and the data we've added to them, lets think about what we want to see in a better light. What are some of the inherent things about a Pokemon that makes them good?

These are just a few of the things we can discern from our dataset, but it gives us a good head start on what to consider. Let's also make some constants for us to use for labeling and plotting!

What makes a strong Pokemon?¶

Let's look at some of the stuff that is inherent to a pokemon, and look at how that affects tiering.

How are types distributed across competitive formats?¶

Let's take a look at what's going on here, codewise.

  • subplots() generates a set of matplotlib graphs that would go together.
    • The first two parameters indicate the dimensions of the graph set.
    • figsize notes the size of the overall figure.
    • sharex (and sharey, later) tells the subplots to use the same x or y axis, including scale.
    • gridspec_kw contains parameters to specify how the grid of graphs is set. hspace and wspace are the heights and widths of the spacing between the graphs.
    • fig is the overall figure that is returned to us from the method.
    • axs is the returned collection of the subplots that we can index.
  • pltrow and pltcol help us dynamically determine what subplot to plot on.
  • loc is a pandas method that allows us to pick out certain rows from the dataframe.
  • bar() is the matplotlib method that creates the bar chart for us.
    • The first two parameters take lists containing corresponding x and y entries.
    • color sets the colors of the bars to be returned.
    • width sets the width of the bars. We set it to 1.0 to reduce padding in between bars.
  • set_title sets the title.
    • The first parameter is the title itself.
    • x and y mark the relative offset of the title.
    • fontsize is self explanatory.
  • set_xticklabels sets the labels of the x axis.
    • labels sets our labels.
    • rotation sets the orientation of the labels.
  • grid is a method that determines the background grid. Setting it to False removes it.
  • text is a method that adds text. We run it on fig because we want the scaling to be relative to the entire figure.
    • The first two parameters are the x and y offsets.
    • The third parameter is the actual text.
    • ha and va are horizontal and vertical alignments.
    • The other parameters are the same as aforementioned.
  • show just shows the graph.

That was a lot, but if you didn't read it, you still get to see the fruits of the labor.

As you can see, dragon as a type averages higher total stats than the other types. Even in individual stats, dragon tends to be at the upper end. This may mean that dragon pokemon tend to just be stronger as a type, which could make up for its poor coverage and defensive strength.

One thing to note is the strongest types for each stat. Fighting is the king of attack, whereas Fire is the king of special attack. Defensively, Steel and Rock massively top the charts, and Flying and Electric are in the leaderboard for speed.

However, the issue with this graph is that we don't see distributions of these stats. For the highest power pokemon, we care about the upper echelons, not the average. Mean as a summary statistic is particularly weak to outliers, and its usually the outliers that we want. Let's see if we can figure out a good way to do this...

One way to view a distribution of points is a boxplot. Let's use the boxplot function found in seaborn, which can automatically make multiple boxplots divided categorically, and all we have to do is pass it a capable dataframe.

To do this, we're going to make a new dataframe, iterate through every pokemon, and add an entry of its stats for each type that it has. That means if a pokemon is, say, fire/flying, we'd add two entries that are numerically identical, but have their respective types that seperate them. Here's the code to make that dataframe below!

In [43]:
# List of columns
stattypes_cols = ['type','atk','dfn','spa','spd','spe','hp','total_stats']

# Make the empty DataFrame
df_stattypes = pd.DataFrame(columns = stattypes_cols)

# Start iterating through the rows. 
for idx, row in df_master.iterrows():
    # Make appropriate no. of entries
    for cur_type in pokemon_types:
        if row['is_'+cur_type]:
            entry = [cur_type]
            total = 0
            for cur_stat in stats:
                total += int(row[cur_stat])
                entry.append(int(row[cur_stat]))
            entry.append(total)
            e = pd.Series(entry, index = stattypes_cols)
            df_stattypes = df_stattypes.append(e, ignore_index = True)

The only new thing here is boxplot and its parameters.

  • x and y are the x and y that we're going to graph the distribution of. We graph the distribution of y, categorized by x.
  • data is the dataframe holding the stuff we're looking for.
  • order is an ordinal list depicting the order to plot categorical data in.
  • ax is the target matplotlib axis to plot on.
  • palette designates the colors we'll use.

How are stats distributed across competitive formats?¶

There's a bit of new code here.

  • The parameter hue for boxplot() gives us split boxplots based on the parameter. Here, we use this to see the difference in distributions for those that are in a tier and in borderline.
  • legend() lets us modify the text in the legend, along with the location of it.
  • xticks() is the same thing as set_xticks(), but for the figure as a whole. Additionally, calling it with no parameters returns a list of the locations and the text of the labels.
  • set() in seaborn is just a way for us to set the style of the seaborn plot.

Let's see the results!

How to Build a Strong Pokemon¶

Now that we've sort of taken a look at what inherently makes a Pokemon good to work with in a competitive scene, let's look at what we could generally do to optimize our Pokemon.

Pokemon have EV's and IV's, but those go into specific minutia about specific interactions between pokemon, surviving hits with barely any HP from popular pokemon, outspeeding others by just 1, and other interesting interactions directly between strong pokemon. We're interested in general trends.

What can someone do other than EV's and IV's to optimize their pokemon? There's some stuff to consider with the choices that are made in making a competitive moveset:

  • What types of moves are the most common in a moveset?
  • What items are most commonly used in competitive?
  • What natures are most commonly used in competitive, and what stats do they increase/decrease?
  • How strong are competitive Pokemon's abilities?

How Strong are Pokemon's Abilities across tiers?¶

Remember our wierd ability-use-ratio score? Let's try and see this wierd distribution. Here, we use seaborn's violinplot. This is kind of like a box plot in the sense that it shows us the distribution of points in a dataset. However, it differs in the sense that it is better at showing densities of distributions rather than the numerical values of various summary statistics. This is key for plotting our ability score, as the range of possible values is so small.

Let's talk about some of the differences in code here.

  • form_delete_list returns us a list of columns based on an input format. The columns in question are the ones that are NOT relevant to the tier that we try to collect the data for. We use the return value to drop irrelevant columns.
  • list and zip allow us to combine lists into a format that allows us to make it into a DataFrame. This allows us to form a relevant dataframe for us to plot.
  • append allows us to add dataframes together. This helps us form a master dataframe for us to plot with seaborn.
  • cut and scale are parameters for seaborn's violinplot which allow us to change how individual violin plots are displayed. cut lets us prevent the viloin plot's density from extending past the range of the actual data, and setting scale to area makes the plot curve around density.

Let's see the results of our code!

In [57]:
# Helper Function
def form_delete_list(form):
    lst = []
    for form in smog_forms:
        if form != form:
            lst.append(form)
            lst.append(form + '_ratio')
    return lst

# Final DataFrame to plot
df_abil_score = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['form','abil_score'])

# Make ability score distributions based on tier.
for form in smog_forms:
    df_form = df_abils.copy()

    df_form = df_form.drop(columns = to_delete)
    df_form = df_form[df_form[form] > 0]
    abil_score = df_form[(form+'_ratio')].copy()
    form_list = [form for i in range(0,len(abil_score))]
    temp_df = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(form_list, abil_score)), 
               columns =['form', 'abil_score'])
    df_abil_score = df_abil_score.append(temp_df)

# Make the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize = [15,10], sharey = True, sharex = True)
sns.set(style='whitegrid')
ax = sns.violinplot(x='form', y = 'abil_score', data = df_abil_score, cut = 0, scale = "area",
                 showmeans = True, order = smog_forms, color = 'lightblue')

Machine Learning¶

What exactly is machine learning?

Tom T. Mitchell defines Machine Learning (ML) as the following:

"A computer program is said to learn from experience E with respect to some class of tasks T and performance measure P if its performance at tasks in T, as measured by P, improves with experience E."

In layman's terms, you give a computer some stuff to learn from, and eventually, it gets better at doing that stuff. There are many types of ML, but the one we're going to be dealing with today is known as Supervised Learning.

Like much of ML, supervised learning builds a model that converts a given set of inputs to a desired output. In this case, we actually have some of the outputs that we want to reach. We use this data to build and train a model to do this. Supervised learning is often divided into classification and regression. The former is used when we have discrete values that we want to reach based on a set of inputs, and the latter is used when the values have a range that they can be in.

In our case, our inputs are the various stats about Pokemon, and our output is the Smogon tier that they would be classified in. There are many mathematical models that we can use, but before we even start doing that, we have to get the data to a point where it can be processed by a computer.

Formatting Data For ML¶

What does a computer take as its inputs? Well, a computer can't exactly take a picture or a phrase as an input as-is. Everything has to be converted to numbers. For some of our data, like stats, its not a hard problem, as they're already numerical. For something nominal, like types, it becomes difficult. There's a few ways to do this:

  • Label Encoding essentially takes something and categorical and converts all of its possibilities to numbers. For example, we would say that bug-types correspond to 0, dark corresponds to 1, and so on.
  • Onehot Encoding breaks apart the single input into many inputs, like what we did earlier with the is_(type) columns of our dataframe (guess which one we're gonna use).

Though both are valid, some research shows that Onehot encoding can give us slightly better results. So, we're going to do that with the code we made earlier.

First, since we're going to be modifying some stuff in the dataframe, lets copy a new one, and check some of the columns.

Classification Algorithms¶

We're going to be comparing 4 algorithms. Some of these algorithms have hyperparameters, which determine how some of these calculations take place.

  • Decision Tree
  • Random Forest
  • K-Nearest-Neighbors
  • Support Vector Machines

Decision Tree¶

The decision tree is an algorithm that classifies stuff by making a tree. It creates a set of criteria at each node, directing you to one of its children based on if it meets said criteria. At the leaves, we should have the class that you (are expected to) belong to.

sklearn's tree has a few hyperparameters. We can find out more about these in the documentation, but I'll explain the ones we use here.

  • criterion determines how the set of criteria in a node are determined. gini gets us a splitter that makes the gini coefficient more pure (percentage chance of incorrect guess gets lowered.)
  • max_depth determines how deep the tree gets. None lets us go until only one class is in a leaf.
  • max_features determines how many features exist in each node when deciding how to split.

Additionally, the methods fit and score actually apply the tree creation onto our data and test the accuracy of the model. Let's first see what a tree looks like, using some code we find online for visualization.

from sklearn import tree

tree_model = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion = 'gini', max_depth = None, max_features = None)

Now, let's get our score! I have a feeling it'll be pretty good...

In [65]:
score = tree_model.score(poke_inputs, poke_targets) * 100
print('We have ' + str(score) + '% accuracy of our model!')

We have 100.0% accuracy of our model!

Wow. 100% accuracy. But here's an issue. We're doing something called overfitting. If we have some missing data, what happens to our accuracy score? sklearn has a library called train_test_split, which allows us to split up our inputs and corresponding outputs into a training group and a test group. Before, our training group was our test group. obviously, this doesn't really mean much for classifying unknown stuff if we already know its proper classification.

  • train_test_split does the splitting, and puts it ino 4 outputs for us.
  • test_size determines how much of the sample we'll use as a test, in this case 10%.
  • random_state determines the seed that we randomly choose our test sample from. We just keep it as 0 to have consistent results, this shouldn't matter in general.

Let's see how much worse our performance is.

With this complicated of a model, how could we NOT go wrong?

In [66]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
input_train, input_test, target_train, target_test = train_test_split(poke_inputs, poke_targets, test_size=0.1) 
tree_model.fit(input_train, target_train)
score = tree_model.score(input_test, target_test) * 100
print('We have ' + str(score) + '% accuracy of our model!')

We have 64.81481481481481% accuracy of our model!

Noticeably worse. This is because we tended to overfit. One way to think aboout overfitting is that our training model doesn't fit new data very well. Obviously, this is a problem, as we can recognize trends that don't actually exist in the data.

Anyway, lets look at other models and see how they perform.

Random Forests¶

The random forest is kind of like a decision tree. It uses the same algorithm as a decision tree, but does it several times over. Each time, it omits a part of the training set to make its tree. When all the trees are made, it runs input through several times, and gets the most popular classification.

n_estimators is just the amount of trees we make.

Let's see the code and results!

In [67]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

forest_model = RandomForestClassifier(criterion = 'gini', max_depth = None, max_features = None, 
                                      random_state = 0, n_estimators = 30)
forest_model.fit(input_train, target_train)
forest_model.score(input_test, target_test)
Out[67]:
0.7037037037037037

K-Nearest-Neighbors¶

The nearest neighbors algorithm essentially finds the classes of the data points most similar to our own and gets the average of them.

n_neighbors is the amount of neighbors to consider. I chose 1 because of the lower amount of Ubers against the more populated other classes could give us some problems.

Let's see the results!

In [68]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
neigh_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=1)
neigh_model.fit(input_train, target_train)
neigh_model.score(input_test, target_test)
Out[68]:
0.7592592592592593

Support Vector Machines¶

The Support Vector Machine is an algorithm that splits the set into various classifications based on vectors.

  • kernel chooses the algorithm that the vectors are made based off of. poly is just a polynobial algorithm.
  • gamma is a kernel coefficient. scale just considers all elements as the default.
  • degree is the degree of the polynomial algorithm.

Let's see how this pans out.

In [69]:
from sklearn.svm import SVC
svm_model = SVC(gamma='scale', degree = 7, kernel = 'poly')
svm_model.fit(input_train, target_train)
svm_model.score(input_test, target_test)
Out[69]:
0.6666666666666666

Testing and comparing classification algorithms.¶

We see the score method as a way to test our algorithms. Splitting our training and testing data seems to be a good idea. What we did is called cross validation, and is a good method of testing the results of a classification algorithm. Is there a good way to do this? Yes! sklearn has a method called cross_val_score, which essentially does train_test_split for us repeatedly. Additionally, scipy has a stats library which we use to t-test.

In [70]:
from scipy import stats
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

tree_score = cross_val_score(tree_model, poke_inputs, poke_targets, cv=10)
forest_score = cross_val_score(forest_model, poke_inputs, poke_targets, cv=10)
neigh_score = cross_val_score(neigh_model, poke_inputs, poke_targets, cv=10)
svm_score = cross_val_score(svm_model, poke_inputs, poke_targets, cv=10)

model_scores = [tree_score, forest_score, neigh_score, svm_score]
model_names = ["Tree", "Forest", "Nearest Neighbors", "SVM"]
combos = [[0, 1], [0, 2], [0, 3], [1, 2], [1, 3], [2, 3]]
for idx in combos:
    i = idx[0]
    j = idx[1]
    cur_test = stats.ttest_rel(model_scores[i], model_scores[j])
    print('---------------------------------------------------------------------------')
    print('Paired T-Test between ' + model_names[i] + " and " + model_names[j] + " model.")
    print('T Stat: ' + str(cur_test.statistic))
    print('P Value: ' + str(cur_test.pvalue))
    print('---------------------------------------------------------------------------')

Insight and Future Projects?¶

From this analysis, we learn that it's pretty difficult to classify how good a pokemon will be based on raw stats and types alone. Even the moves it can learn arent quite enough to verify how good it is. This tells us the importance of abilities in competitive pokemon. We also learned the importance of raw statistical power, typing, and speed in particular.

We could extrapolate this to other games with competitive scenes, obviously changing the variables. Being able to generalize the strength of a new game elements can help balance teams to take actions that support the competitive environment. While I did this for the love of Pokemon, I'm sure that companies can use methods like these to understand what's fun for their players.

There were many limitations in this project, such as not accounting for individual moves, but I didn't want to overfit our models. In the future, I may revisit this project to amend this. I also plan to do more work in data pipelines in the future!
